I stopped by on a Sunday morning on my way into Manhattan to do something before the Yom Tov, which was on my mind. And spied that there was this Starbuck's on the way down to the park overlooking a riverside viewpoint of Midtown. In any event I went there afterwards for a medium-sized coffee with extra cream and sugar.  The young man helping me looked a lot like Timothée--- from the actor's latest film "Dune (2021)" ... the ibterior is rather pleasant. Smallish and narrowing. Then easily becomes crowded forming a queue from both ends beginning to end. With just handfuls of people there. But sincerely pleasant.  Outside on this really pretty day there were tables everywhere. Some had chairs. Others none. The homelessness around poked up seeing seated parked sipping coffee as well it seemed. But the air was filled with this strong notoceanle malodorous stench of sewage coming from the water. So it seems. Thinking "Maybe they should dump more clams, oysters, and mussels into the river to clean it up! Now there's an environmental impact statement starter."  In any event, the coffee server was terrific. The dark coffee being overwhelmingly beyond budget again, still, was great to have alongside the outdoor styled Café chairs and tables. A good crowd mix. Between young families with kids or baby strollers. And everyone else in-between. Just a really quaint spot to venture out to.  Romanticism naturally came to mind venturing beyond the liquor. Like "what a great spot for a date or proposal ..." if you took the coffee over to Eleanor's Point to sit or lounge during the night or day. How  lovely.
